B.a1G=s(["Primary Demyelinating Polyneuropathy","A Myopathic process (e.g., Polymyositis)","Severe Axonal Neuropathy"],t.s)
B.a7k=new A.hB("A patient presents with profound proximal muscle weakness, difficulty climbing stairs, and perfectly normal sensory examinations. Needle EMG reveals an early, dense recruitment pattern. What is the most likely diagnosis?",B.a1G,1,"Proximal weakness, preserved sensation, and early recruitment are classic hallmarks of myopathy. The brain recruits surviving weak motor units extremely early to compensate for muscle failure.")
B.a0v=s(["Severely dropped amplitudes but normal conduction velocities","Perfectly normal latencies and velocities","Prolonged latencies and significantly slowed conduction velocities"],t.s)
B.a7j=new A.hB("In a purely demyelinating polyneuropathy, what is the expected finding on standard Sensory Nerve Action Potential (SNAP) testing?",B.a0v,2,"Demyelination destroys the nerve's insulation. The primary resulting dysfunction is slowed conduction velocity and stretched, prolonged piece-to-piece latencies across the demyelinated segments.")
B.a1r=s(["Myopathic muscle fiber necrosis","Chronic neurogenic reinnervation (axonal sprouting)","Acute toxic muscle destruction"],t.s)
B.a7p=new A.hB("You perform a needle EMG on a patient. During voluntary contraction, you observe MUAPs that are extraordinarily tall (giant amplitude) and very wide (long duration). The screen looks incredibly barren with only one or two units firing at rapid speed. What mechanism creates this?",B.a1r,1,"When nerves die, surviving neighboring nerves aggressively 'sprout' to adopt the orphaned muscle fibers. This creates a massive (tall) and spread-out (wide) electrical footprint: the 'Giant' MUAP of chronic reinnervation.")
B.a09=s(["Inflammatory Myopathy","Length-Dependent Peripheral Neuropathy","Focal Muscle Dystrophy"],t.s)
B.a7q=new A.hB("A patient complains of stocking-glove numbness marching up from their toes, absent ankle reflexes, and dropping objects from their hands. What is the likely pathology?",B.a09,1,"Stocking-glove sensory loss, distal weakness, and absent reflexes strongly indicate a length-dependent peripheral neuropathy (the longest nerves dying back first), often due to metabolic causes like Diabetes.")
B.Zt=s(["The nerve fires faster to compensate","The surviving muscle fibers within the unit are fewer, so the electrical wave takes less time to pass","Demyelination causes the signal to shrink in length"],t.s)
B.a7o=new A.hB("Why do we typically see a 'Short Duration' MUAP in an active myopathy?",B.Zt,1,"In myopathy, the nerve is healthy but many of the muscle fibers it commands have died. With fewer workers responding to the nerve's signal, the total electrical ripple created in the muscle is physically shorter in time.")
B.a2p=s(["Steroid myopathy selectively atrophies Type II fibers, while standard EMG primarily records healthier Type I fibers","The weakness is entirely psychological","Steroids enhance nerve conduction velocity to hide the muscle damage"],t.s)
B.a7i=new A.hB("A patient taking high-dose prednisone for months develops severe proximal weakness. Their EMG study appears surprisingly normal with little to no spontaneous activity. Why?",B.a2p,0,"Steroid myopathy is notorious for looking normal on EMG because it selectively targets Type II (fast-twitch) muscle fibers. The needle largely misses this damage because it naturally records the healthier Type I fibers during mild contraction.")
B.Zn=s(["Massive drops in conduction velocity","Severely reduced Compound Muscle Action Potential (CMAP) amplitudes","Focal conduction block across the forearm"],t.s)
B.a7h=new A.hB("In a severe axonal loss motor neuropathy, what is the foundational abnormality seen on the Nerve Conduction Study (NCS)?",B.Zn,1,"Axonal loss means the physical wires are cut or dead. Fewer wires reaching the target muscle means less electricity delivered, yielding a starkly reduced CMAP amplitude. The surviving fibers still conduct at normal velocities.")
B.a_e=s(["Perfectly normal muscle tone","Active denervation: individual orphaned muscle fibers are spontaneously misfiring","A purely demyelinating conduction block"],t.s)
B.a7m=new A.hB("You stick a resting muscle with your EMG needle and hear a sound like 'rain on a tin roof' consisting of Fibrillations and Positive Sharp Waves. What does this mean?",B.a_e,1,"Fibrillations and Positive Sharp Waves are the desperate cries of individual muscle fibers that have been physically separated from their nerve supply. They become hyper-irritable and fire spontaneously while waiting for reinnervation.")
B.ZY=s(["Neuropathy","Myopathy","Both depending on temperature"],t.s)
B.a7n=new A.hB("According to the fundamental 'Rules of Thumb', which scenario represents the 'Labor Shortage' where surviving units must fire incredibly fast to generate any force?",B.ZY,0,"Neuropathy is the Labor Shortage. The axons (workers) die off. To make up the deficit, the few surviving axon units must fire at absolute maximum frequency to maintain strength. Myopathy is the Weak Workforce (too many weak units firing early).")
B.ZL=s(["The screen showing absolutely zero electrical activity during maximum effort","A single motor unit firing clearly and slowly at 10 Hz","A dense, overlapping, chaotic cloud of electrical activity filling the screen during maximal voluntary contraction"],t.s)
B.a7l=new A.hB("Which of the following describes a 'Full Interference Pattern'?",B.ZL,2,"The interference pattern occurs when the patient exerts maximal force. The brain recruits every motor unit available, and they fire so fast and densely that the individual spikes 'interfere' with each other, creating a solid wall of electrical noise.")
B.a2i=s([B.a7k,B.a7j,B.a7p,B.a7q,B.a7o,B.a7i,B.a7h,B.a7m,B.a7n,B.a7l],A.ad("q<hB>"))
