B.a29=s(["Carpal Tunnel","Median Nerve at the Elbow","C6 Nerve Root","Brachial Plexus"],t.s)
B.abh=new A.c2("A patient presents with numbness in the thumb and index finger. The Median SNAP (sensory) is completely normal, but the Biceps and Brachioradialis show denervation. Where is the lesion?",B.a29,2,"This is a classic C6 radiculopathy. The clue is the NORMAL sensory study (SNAP) despite the numbness\u2014this means the pinch is 'Behind the DRG'. The involvement of both the Biceps and Brachioradialis confirms the level.")
B.a0D=s(["To let the pain subside","To allow enough time for fibrillation potentials to develop in the limbs","Because insurance won't pay for it sooner","To allow the disc to heal on its own"],t.s)
B.abB=new A.c2("Why do we wait at least 3 weeks after a sudden disc herniation before doing a full EMG study?",B.a0D,1,"Wallerian degeneration takes time. It takes approximately 2-3 weeks for the distal parts of the nerve in the limbs to show spontaneous activity (fibrillations) after a proximal injury at the root.")
B.a0w=s(["Tibialis Anterior","Extensor Hallucis Longus","Gluteus Medius","Gastroc"],t.s)
B.abO=new A.c2("Which muscle should you check to differentiate an L5 radiculopathy from a Peroneal (Fibular) neuropathy?",B.a0w,2,"The Gluteus Medius is innervated by the Superior Gluteal Nerve (L5), which branches off the plexus BEFORE the peroneal nerve forms. If the Glut Med is abnormal, the lesion must be at or proximal to the plexus/root level.")
B.a_c=s(["Spinal stenosis","Degenerative spondylosis","Herniated nucleus pulposus (disc herniation)","Malignancy"],t.s)
B.abn=new A.c2("What is the most common cause of radiculopathy in a 35-year-old patient?",B.a_c,2,"In patients YOUNGER than 50 years, HERNIATED NUCLEUS PULPOSUS is the most common cause. In patients OLDER than 50, SPINAL STENOSIS becomes more prevalent.")
B.ZS=s(["Achilles reflex","Patellar reflex","Biceps reflex","Medial hamstring reflex"],t.s)
B.abI=new A.c2("Which reflex is associated with L4 radiculopathy?",B.ZS,1,"L4 radiculopathy affects the PATELLAR (knee jerk) reflex. The reflex patterns are: L4 = patellar, L5 = medial hamstring, S1 = Achilles.")
B.Z6=s(["Disc herniation","Spinal stenosis","Inflammatory radiculitis","Athletic injury"],t.s)
B.abk=new A.c2("A 60-year-old patient presents with progressive back pain and bilateral leg weakness. What is the most likely etiology?",B.Z6,1,"In older patients, spinal stenosis due to degenerative changes is the leading cause, often presenting with bilateral symptoms.")
B.a28=s(["0-5%","10-30%","50-70%","90-100%"],t.s)
B.abw=new A.c2("What percentage of radiculopathy cases may have paraspinal abnormalities as the ONLY EMG finding?",B.a28,1,"Paraspinal abnormalities are found as the sole indicator in 10-30% of cases, making paraspinal examination crucial for root localization.")
B.a1m=s(["EMG timeline","Myotomal patterns","Non-mechanical causes","Reflex associations"],t.s)
B.abt=new A.c2("What does the 'HI MADAM' mnemonic help remember?",B.a1m,2,"'HI MADAM' covers non-mechanical causes like Herpes, Inflammatory, Metastasis, Arachnoiditis, Diabetes, Abscess, and Mass.")
